 for much of his life the Clifton R. Musser Professor Emeritus of Economics at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago_Law_School\" title=\"University of Chicago Law School\">University of Chicago Law School<\/a>, where he arrived in 1964 and remained for the rest of his life. After studying with the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_London_External_Programme\" title=\"University of London External Programme\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of London External Programme<\/a> in 1927\u201329, Coase entered the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/London_School_of_Economics\" title=\"London School of Economics\">London School of Economics<\/a>, where he took courses with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Arnold_Plant\" title=\"Arnold Plant\">Arnold Plant<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Coase_Autobiography_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Coase#cite_note-Coase_Autobiography-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Economics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Economics\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize in Economics<\/a> in 1991.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Coase#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Coase, who believed economists should study real markets and not theoretical ones, established the case for the corporation as a means to pay the costs of operating a marketplace.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_Coase#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> Coase is best known for two articles in particular: \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Nature_of_the_Firm\" title=\"The Nature of the Firm\">The Nature of the Firm<\/a>\" (1937), which introduces the concept of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Transaction_cost\" title=\"Transaction cost\">transaction costs<\/a> to explain the nature and limits of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Corporation\" title=\"Corporation\">firms<\/a>, and \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Problem_of_Social_Cost\" title=\"The Problem of Social Cost\">The Problem of Social Cost<\/a>\" (1960), which suggests that well-defined <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Property_rights_(economics)\" title=\"Property rights (economics)\">property rights<\/a> could overcome the problems of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Externalities\" title=\"Externalities\" class=\"mw-redirect\">externalities<\/a> (see <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Coase_theorem\" title=\"Coase theorem\">Coase theorem<\/a>). Coase is also often referred to as the \"father\" of reform in the policy for allocation of the electromagnetic <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Broadcast_license\" title=\"Broadcast license\">spectrum<\/a>, based on his article \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/The_Federal_Communications_Commission\" title=\"The Federal Communications Commission\" class=\"mw-redirect\">The Federal Communications Commission<\/a>\" (1959), where he criticises spectrum licensing, suggesting property rights as a more efficient method of allocating spectrum to users. Additionally, Coase's transaction costs approach is currently influential in modern organizational economics, where it was reintroduced by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Oliver_E._Williamson\" title=\"Oliver E. Williamson\">Oliver E. Williamson<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Ronald Coase","place_of_birth":"Willesden near London","place_of_death":"Chicago ,  Illinois ,  United States","text":"Ronald Coase , based in the United States  Economics, 1991","year":1991.0}